e and fix the `bid_budget_optimizer` duplication loop.**\nThe agent fired the same `schedule_status_change` action ~28 times in rapid succession this morning. While no changes were applied, this creates log noise and could — if the `applied` flag ever fails — result in redundant API calls or unintended campaign state changes. Prioritize a deduplication fix before the next active day.\n\n3. **Revisit the Meta ad group flagged at $12.15 CPL before resuming Meta spend.**\nRather than simply blocking scale on this unit, determine *why* CPL is this low. Either the conversion event is misconfigured (e.g., firing on page load rather than form submit), the audience is too broad for Ridgecrest's affluent homeowner target, or ad creative is attracting the wrong segment. Do not resume spend on this ad group until the tracking and audience configuration is confirmed clean.\n\n4. **Use Wednesday's pause to prepare Thursday pre-launch checks.**\nSince Thursday is also an inactive day, leverage today and tomorrow to refresh ad creative, confirm geo-targeting is tightly scoped to East Bay/Contra Costa zip codes, and validate that all conversion tracking is firing correctly — so campaigns re-launch Friday with clean data integrity.\n\n5. **Reaffirm $125/day Google Ads cap discipline heading into the active weekend.**\nThe `bid_budget_optimizer` flagged campaigns as "near weekly ceiling" and attempted reallocation to fit the $250/day portfolio cap. Confirm that Google Ads campaigns are individually capped at $125/day and that the optimizer's reallocation logic does not inadvertently push Google Ads above its platform-specific limit when budgets are redistributed across channels on active days.\n\n---	{"cpl": null, "spend": 0.0, "clicks": 0, "avg_cpc": 0.0, "avg_ctr": 0.0, "conversions": 0.0, "impressions": 0, "platform_breakdown": {}}	\N	reporting_agent	2026-03-25 08:01:47.630771+00	all
