get_optimizer` | Budget Reallocation | Campaign (×15) | Near weekly ceiling — scaling to fit $250.00/day available | ❌ Not Applied |\n| `meta_manager` | Quality Alert | Ad Group (×2) | CPL $119.27 is below $150 floor — verify lead quality before scaling | ❌ Not Applied |\n\n> ⚠️ **Note:** All optimization actions were generated but **none were applied.** This warrants investigation — if the automation system is consistently failing to execute queued actions, campaign controls may not be functioning as intended.\n\n---\n\n### Alerts & Flags\n\n**🟡 Warning — Inactive Day Enforcement Not Applied**\nThe system correctly identified Wednesday as an inactive ad day and generated 29 separate `schedule_status_change` actions across campaigns. However, `applied: false` on all of them means campaigns were not programmatically paused. Confirm manually that no spend leaked today through platform-side scheduling gaps.\n\n**🟡 Warning — Budget Reallocation Actions Not Applied**\n15 `budget_reallocation` actions were queued (citing proximity to weekly spend ceiling) but not executed. With $681.51 already spent over 7 days against a $250/day cap, pacing should be reviewed to ensure the weekly ceiling isn't being breached on active days.\n\n**🔵 Info — CPL Quality Alert: $119.27 Below Floor**\nThe `meta_manager` flagged an ad group delivering leads at $119.27 CPL — below the $150 quality floor. While a lower CPL might seem favorable, Ridgecrest's luxury positioning requires lead quality validation before treating this as a scaling signal. Cheap leads in a high-intent, high-ticket vertical often indicate mis-targeted audiences or low-intent form fills.\n\n**🔵 Info — 7-Day CPL at $170.38**\nBlended CPL over the trailing week is $170.38, sitting above the $150 floor — acceptable, but worth monitoring. At 4 conversions on $681.51 in spend, volume remains low. For a design-build firm with project values likely exceeding $100K, CPL efficiency matters less than lead quality and close rate.\n\