d group until lead quality is verified.**\n\n**🟡 Notice — 7-Day CPL at $170.38**\nThe 7-day CPL is within range but on the higher end for 4 conversions across $681.51 in spend. With a small sample size, a single unqualified lead can skew this metric significantly. Conversion quality review is warranted.\n\n---\n\n### Recommendations\n\n1. **Resolve the automation pipeline before tomorrow's launch.**\n   Every optimization action generated today shows `applied: false`. Before campaigns go live Thursday, confirm that bid adjustments and budget reallocations are actually being pushed to Google Ads and Meta. A broken write-back loop means the account is flying blind — recommendations are generated but never executed.\n\n2. **Manually audit the below-floor Meta ad group before scaling.**\n   The ad group producing a $119.27 CPL needs a lead-by-lead quality review. Cross-reference form submissions against Ridgecrest's client profile (homeowner, East Bay / Contra Costa, $500K+ project intent). If leads are unqualified, tighten audience targeting — income layers, homeownership status, and ZIP-level geo restrictions — rather than scaling volume at a low CPL that doesn't convert to consultations.\n\n3. **Prioritize highest-performing campaigns in tomorrow's budget allocation.**\n   With the weekly spend pacing near the ceiling and a $250/day active-day cap, budget reallocation should flow toward campaigns that contributed to the 4 conversions over the last 7 days. Confirm which campaigns drove those conversions before the optimizer reallocates spend based on incomplete logic (given the `applied: false` issue).\n\n4. **Enforce Google Ads sub-cap discipline at the campaign level.**\n   The $250/day daily cap is account-wide. Ensure Google Ads campaigns are individually capped to prevent the paid search budget from consuming the full daily allowance and leaving Meta underfunded — or vice versa. Given Ridgecrest's premium positioning, maintaining presence on both platforms (brand